Title : Sunil Sabharwal
Text : {{Orphan|date=May 2014}}

'''Sunil Sabharwal'''(in Punjabi ਸੁਨੀਲ ਸਭਰਵਾਲ) is the Alternate Executive Director of the International Monetary Fund, to which he was appointed by the White House on April 3, 2014.<ref name="whitehouse.gov">{{cite news|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/04/07/presidential-nominations-sent-senate}}</ref> He is an independent business investor and advisor of Indian-Hungarian descent who escaped from the [[Hungarian People's Republic]] in 1983 and returned in 1992 after the collapse of communism to set up the Budapest office of the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]] (EBRD).<ref name="The New York Times">{{cite news|last=Nash|first=Nathaniel|title=Privatizing in Hungary: A Door Opens|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/17/business/international-business-privatizing-in-hungary-a-door-reopens.html?src=pm|accessdate=4 March 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 17, 1995}}</ref> Most recently, he was Chairman of the Board of [[Ogone]], a European Internet payment services company with headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.  A former NCAA All-American and Big Ten Champion in fencing, he serves on a commission of the [[International Olympic Committee]], the [[International Fair Play Committee]] and Peace & Sport, USA.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newman|first=Barry|title=Another Daunting Olympic Quest: The Search for Gallant Behavior|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB121876678865243331|date=August 15, 2008}}</ref> He speaks publicly on investing in Central and Eastern Europe, the confluence of sport, business and the environment, and the role of international financial institutions in a changing economy.

== Early life and education ==

He was born in 1964 in [[New Delhi]], [[India]] to Baldev Raj Sabharwal, a printing entrepreneur who founded the New Roxy Press in New Delhi, and Gabriella Bessenyey, of Hungarian descent.  He attended the Frank Anthony school in New Delhi, India and the Imre Madach High school in Budapest Hungary.

== Escape from People's Republic of Hungary ==

Sabharwal's mother struggled in Hungary under the communist regime because she refused to join the communist party.  When she tried to sell pottery to feed her family, authorities wouldn't grant her a vendor's license. The family went to Vienna during the summer of 1983 under the auspices of a cultural tour and pleaded for asylum at the US Embassy, citing political and religious oppression. They gained sponsorship from the Upper Arlington Lutheran Church in Columbus, Ohio with particular support from Ohio State faculty member David Cole and his wife Edie and arrived in Columbus, Ohio in December 1983.<ref name=Welzel>{{cite news|last=Welzel|first=Karen A.|title=Refugees Find Christmas '83 Brighter|newspaper=Columbus Dispatch|date=December 15, 1983}}</ref>  Once in the Columbus Hungarian-American network, Sabharwal met OSU fencing coach and Hungarian [http://library.osu.edu/blogs/archives/2012/01/17/in-remembrance-charlotte-remenyik-osu-fencing-coach/ Charlotte Remenyik.]

== Education ==

Sabharwal enrolled at Ohio State University in January 1984, excelling in both business administration studies and fencing. He was OSU's 1984 Big Ten Champion and NCAA All-American in 1984 and 1986.<ref>{{cite news|last=Loader|first=Deborah|title=Fencers to Host 13-Team Meet|newspaper=The Lantern|date=January 25, 1985}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Aborn|first=Janice|title=Fencers Achieve Recognition with Skill|newspaper=The Lantern (OSU)|date=March 7, 1984}}</ref> In 1988 he won OSU's Jack Stephenson Award{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} for Outstanding Scholastic and Academic Achievement at the College of Business and graduated cum laude with a Bachelor of Science degree with Distinction in Marketing. He earned his Master of Science degree in Management at [[London Business School]] in 1996 and a diploma in Company Direction from [[Institute of Directors|UK's Institute of Directors]] in 2009.

== Return to Post-Communist Hungary ==

In 1992 he returned to post-Communist Hungary to set up the Budapest office of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), an international finance institution created specifically to foster the transition of post-Soviet economies backed by the developed world. Soon after its establishment the EBRD became the largest investor in Central and Eastern Europe and Hungary, one of its largest fund recipients.<ref name="Parliamentary Assembly of The Council of Europe">{{cite web|title=The contribution of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) to economic development in central and eastern Europe|url=http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/Doc/XrefViewHTML.asp?FileID=10180&Language=EN|publisher=Parliamentary Assembly of The Council of Europe|accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=Ipsen>{{cite news|last=Ipsen|first=Erik|title=EBRD Charts Its Rocky Path|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/10/20/business/worldbusiness/20iht-ebrd.html|accessdate=27 February 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 20, 1994}}</ref>

== Financial Services Sector Career ==

Sabharwal had a 10-year private equity and mergers and acquisitions career with [http://www.gecapital.eu/en/index.html GE Capital] in London and [[Western Union|First Data / Western Union]], in London and Paris.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bloomberg|title=Executive Profile: Sunil Sabharwal|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=730915&privcapId=28532&previousCapId=558652&previousTitle=Euromedic%20International%20Kft|publisher=Bloomberg/Businessweek|accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>  He served on the board of Euromedic [http://www.euromedic.com/index Euromedic], Central Europe's largest private healthcare services organization.

== Current ==

Sabharwal resides in Washington, D.C. independently advising and co-investing with private equity firms and financial services corporations. He is married to Gabrielle Tabori Sabharwal and has two children, Nicolas and Izabella.

== Civic works ==

He is a member of the [[International Olympic Committee]]’s Sport and Environment Commission{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} and was Treasurer, now Secretary-General, of the UNESCO- and IOC-affiliated [[International Fair Play Committee]]. He also serves on the board of [http://www.peace-sport.us/ Peace & Sport USA]. He was Chairman of the International Fencing Federation's (FIE) first annual Congress held in the U.S., in Philadelphia in 2011<ref name=FIE>{{cite web|title=FIE Congress 100|url=http://www.fie.org/en/news/fie-congress-2011-0-1194|publisher=FIE|accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref> and Chief of Mission to the US Olympic Fencing team at the Beijing Olympics in 2008.

